07945nam a22010815i 9789048543854DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20212020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485438547 a10.1515/97890485438542doi  a(DE-B1597)567841  a(OCoLC)1233041403  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0150802bisacsh00aReconstruction, Replication and Re-enactment in the Humanities and Social Sciences /ced. by Patricia Lulof, Anna Harris, Sven Dupré, Julia Kursell, Maartje Stols-Witlox. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (298 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1. Replication as a Play on Categories: The Case of Taxidermy -- t2. Bringing the Past to Life : Material Culture Production and Archaeological Practice -- t3. Making Musicians Think: The Problem with Organs -- t4. Making Sound Present: Re-enactment and Reconstruction in Historical Organ Building Practices -- t5. Reconstructions of Oil Painting Materials and Techniques : The HART Model for Approaching Historical Accuracy -- t6. Imperfect Copies. Reconstructions in Conservation Research and Practice -- t7. Reworking Recipes and Experiments in the Classroom -- t8. A Walk as Act / Enact / Re-enactment: Performing Psychogeography and Anthropology -- t9. Recreating Reconstructions: Archaeology, Architecture and 3D Technologies -- t10. Science and the Knowing Body : Making Sense of Embodied Knowledge in Scientific Experiment -- tIndex of RRR Terminology -- tIndex of Keywords0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerformative methods are playing an increasingly prominent role in research into historical production processes, materials, and bodily knowledge and sensory skills, and in forms of education and public engagement in classrooms and museums. This book offers, for the first time, sustained, interdisciplinary reflections on performative methods, variously known as Reconstruction, Re-enactment, Replication, Reproduction and Reworking (RRR) practices across the fields of history of science, archaeology, art history, conservation, musicology and anthropology. Each of these fields has distinct histories, approaches, tools and research questions. Researchers in the historical disciplines have used reconstructions to learn about the materials and practices of the past, while anthropologists and ethnographers have more often studied the re-enactments themselves, participating in these performances as engaged observers. In this book, an interdisciplinary group of authors bring their experiences of RRR practices within their discipline into conversation with RRR practices in other disciplines, providing a basis for interdisciplinary cross-fertilization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aArchiving, Conservation and Digitization. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aDiachronic. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  areconstruction, replication, re-enactment, performance, methodology.1 aCarlyle, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupré, Sven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupré, Sven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFidom, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagendijk, Thijs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeering, Peter, ec